1. List of key files
--------------------

  README                            - This is README file
  ReleaseNote.txt                   - List of changes between current releases to
                                      previous release version
  ReleaseNote_fw_<chip>.txt         - <chip> firmware release notes.
  bcm_pm_if                         - PHYMOD Interface functionalities
  bcm_plp_sec or bcm_plp_base_t_sec - CfyE and SecY Interface functionality or SecY interface support
  DDK or IMACSEC                    - CfyE and SecY source or SecY support
  doc                               - Documentation (using Doxygen)
  <chip>_reference_app              - Sample application to access phy chip
  make                              - make rules and config files
  Makefile                          - Makefile provides 'build' and 'clean' the targets
  phymod/acc                        - Platform specific register access mechanism
  phymod/chip                       - All supported CHIPs
  phymod/chip/<chip>                - chip specific functionalities
  phymod/core                       - PHYMOD APIs for dispatch,access,diagnostics and
                                      debug
  phymod/diag                       - PHYMOD diag APIs for eyescan,dsc.. etc
  phymod/doc                        - Documentation for phymod (using Doxygen)
  phymod/include                    - Header files, phymod custom config header file
  phymod/include/phymod             - PHYMOD APIs related header files
  phymod/include/phymod/acc         - PHYMOD APIs access header files
  phymod/include/phymod/chip        - PHYMOD APIs chip related header files


2. How to compile
------------------

To compile, unpack it to a directory and run

 To Unpack
 ---------

 tar -zxvf <CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>.tgz

 To compile
 ----------
 cd <CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>.tgz
 make clean
 make

3. An example of how to write a sample program to access software driver library using EPDM
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Application users have to download EPDM(External PHY Device manager) to their code to access phy drivers.

All supported EPDM APIs are listed under $EPDM/epdm.h and $EPDM/epdm_sec.h(for DDK) or $EPDM/epdm_base_t_sec.h(for IMACSEC).

-> User needs to set $EPDM_HOME in Makefile with the EPDM source code location
-> User needs to implement the MDIO read/write callbacks. Reference implementation is available in $<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>/<chip>_reference_app/<chip>_common.c
-> Below PHY families support Clause 22 MDIO read/write callbacks only
   BCM541XX (Broncos, Seahawks)
   BCM542XX (Ravens, Rams, Giants, Cowboys)
   BCM502XX (Cowboys)

 Example Application program:
 ----------------------------
 $<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>/<chip>_reference_app have an example of accessing PHY driver library through EPDM


4. How to access documentation
-------------------------------
See the included doc pages for more information on $<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>.

 Documentation pages available at $<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>/doc/html/index.html
5. How to specify firmware download method
----------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Broadcast Firmware Download
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Broadcast Firmware download is a method to broadcast firmware on all phy devices connected on same MDIO bus. Broadcast is supported by MDIO download method.
Application has to follow below steps to start the broadcast firmware download using this API:

int bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast(char* chip_name, bcm_plp_access_t phy_info,
                          int (*read)(void* user_acc, unsigned int core_addr, unsigned int reg_addr, unsigned int* val),
                          int (*write)(void* user_acc, unsigned int core_addr, unsigned int reg_addr, unsigned int val),
                          bcm_plp_firmware_load_type_t *firmware_load_type,
                          bcm_plp_firmware_broadcast_method_t broadcast_method);

firmware_load_type.firmware_load_method     Specify the firmware load method
0 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodNone             Do not download firmware
1 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodInternal         Internal Firmware Download: MDIO download
2 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodExternal         Load FW using a user registered function
3 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodProgEEPROM       Load FW and flash it into EEPROM

firmware_load_type.force_load_method        Force firmware load method
0 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadSkip                   Skip firmware download if firmware is already present
1 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadForce                  Always download the firmware specified by firmware load method
2 - bcmpmFirmwareLoadAuto                   Check the firmware version: if it is different from current version download the firmware,
                                            otherwise skip the download
Following steps are followed for broadcast method:
firmware_load_type.firmware_load_method=bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodInternal;
firmware_load_type.force_load_method=bcmpmFirmwareLoadForce;

Identify list of PHY's that needs to be broadcasted on a MDIO Bus which is refered as BCAST_LIST, To perform broadcast follow below steps,
i)   For each PHY in BCAST_LIST call,
     bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write, &firmware_load_type, bcmpmFirmwareBroadcastCoreReset); ## This Hard reset the core.

ii)  For each PHY in BCAST_LIST call,
     bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write, &firmware_load_type, bcmFirmwareBroadcastEnable); ## Enable Broadcast mode, Broadcast Starts

iii) Load Firmware for any one Phy/Core in BCAST_LIST,
     bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write, &firmware_load_type, bcmFirmwareBroadcastFirmwareExecute); ## Download MICROCODE

iv)  For each PHY in BCAST_LIST call,
     bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write, &firmware_load_type, bcmFirmwareBroadcastFirmwareVerify); ## verify FW

v)   For each PHY in BCAST_LIST call,
     bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write, &firmware_load_type, bcmFirmwareBroadcastEnd); ## End of broadcast

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unicast Firmware Download
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unicast firmware download can also be acheived through "bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast", By calling with bcmFirmwareBroadcastNone API as follows,
  bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast("chip_name",phy_info, read, write,&firmware_load_type,bcmFirmwareBroadcastNone);


6. Microcode Release
--------------------
i) Hex version of microcode(firmware) file, <chip>_ucode.c available in
$<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>/phymod/chip/<phy chip>/tier1

<Version> denotes the version of the firmware.
<chip>    denotes the phy chip

7. Floating Point Library Requirement:
--------------------------------------
bcm_pm_if_eye_margin_proj API requires floating point library support.
User has to compile ePIL with SERDES_API_FLOATING_POINT in config.mk as mentioned below(conditional compilation flag, specified in make file with -D option)
for enabling bcm_pm_if_eye_margin_proj API support.

TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DSERDES_API_FLOATING_POINT
before
export PHYMOD_EPIL_DSYM_CPPFLAGS

Please note that the user must add -DSERDES_API_FLOATING_POINT in user application Makefile if epdm.h file is used due to a newer version of EPDM is being used

8. To enable debug message for register read and write:
-------------------------------------------------------
Add TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DPHYMOD_DEBUG_BUS_WRITE -DPHYMOD_DEBUG_BUS_READ in make\config.mk file

9. Updating PRE defined PHYMOD macro with user defined macro/API
----------------------------------------------------------------
PHYMOD provides a way to update pre defined macro with user defined API.
User needs to update macros in $<CHIP>_<Y>_<Z>/phymod/include/phymod_custom_config.h based on user environment.

eg: #define PHYMOD_USLEEP        user_usleep

10. Port Macro Warmboot Support(does not include Macsec Warmboot, for Macsec Warmboot, see section 10.1)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Application has to follow below steps to perform warmboot,

   1. To enable driver to supports warmboot,
       Compile with TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT -DBCM_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT in make\config.mk file

   2. To use warmboot feature,
       Call bcm_plp_init API or bcm_plp_init_fw_bcast API (for broadcast enabled init) with
       flags(under bcm_plp_info structure) as BCM_PLP_WARM_BOOT.
       For MACSEC module(This applies for Evora/Europa/Miura chipsets only),
          Call bcm_plp_cyfe_device_init with flags(under bcm_plp_info structure) as BCM_PLP_WARM_BOOT and
          Call bcm_plp_secy_device_init with flags(under bcm_plp_info structure) as BCM_PLP_WARM_BOOT.

    3. Choose  FW load method as below:
          fw_load_type.firmware_load_method = bcmpmFirmwareLoadMethodNone;
          fw_load_type.force_load_method    = bcmpmFirmwareLoadSkip;

NOTE: For cold boot it is expected to clear flags (under bcm_plp_info structure)

10.1 MACSEC Warmboot(for applicable chip families)
-----------------------------------------------------
     - This feature when enabled, helps to save and restore running Macsec Configuration.
     - Enable Port Macro Warmboot in the previous section 10, if enabling Macsec Warmboot
       Macsec Pre-warmboot:
     - Compile the driver with MACSEC enabled
     - Compile the driver with -DBCM_PLP_MACSEC_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT enabled in make/config.mk
         * Uncomment #TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MACSEC_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT in make/config.mk
         * During Pre-warmboot or coldboot of the PHY device, Configure PHY for macsec and save all the needed macsec config in persistent memory(files /tmp/warmbootfile0../tmp/warmbootfile8)
           see reference app aperta_macsec_transform_pre_warmboot_100G_4x25G_NRZ.c
       Macsec Warmboot:
     - Compile the driver with MACSEC enabled
     - Compile the driver with -DBCM_PLP_MACSEC_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT enabled in make/config.mk
         * Uncomment #TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MACSEC_WARM_BOOT_SUPPORT in make/config.mk
         * Macsec configuration is not required, see reference app, aperta_macsec_transform_warmboot_100G_4x25G_NRZ.c for Aperta chip family.
         *This will Warmboot the PHY device, and restore all macsec config from persistent memory(files /tmp/warmbootfile0../tmp/warmbootfile8)
         *
         * When the driver is initialized and runs, it uses the provided callback
         * functions to allocate space to store driver state and to write updated
         * driver state. The callback functions are responsible for maintaining
         * the stored state in a memory that will be preserved when the CPU is
         * restarted.
         *
         * Warm boot: the hardware device remains operational, while the CPU running
         * the software is restarted. This restart can be either planned or unexpected.
         *
         * For a planned warm boot, the application is supposed to call
         * bcm_plp_warmboot_shutdown() for each of the data items allocated by the
         * driver through this API. This allows the driver to relinquish
         * software resources without shutting down the hardware devices, so
         * the CPU can restart in an orderly manner.
         * For an unexpected warm boot, bcm_plp_warmboot_shutdown() will not be called.
         * After a warm boot:
         * - bcm_plp_warmboot_register()
         *        to register callbacks with the API.
         * - For each of the data items allocated by the driver through this API:
         *   - bcm_plp_warmboot_restore()
         *        to restore all driver internal state, which corresponds to the
         *        state of the running hardware.
         * No other driver API calls are permitted before the last bcm_plp_warmboot_restore() call returns.

11. Using EPDM with multiple chip family drivers
------------------------------------------------
    If user intends to use an EPDM version that is different (and newer) than the one released with the PHY driver
    the following steps need to be followed to enable the driver to use epdm common defines.
       Step 1: Uncomment and define EPDM_HOME based on your EPDM installation directory in make\config.mk file
       Step 2: Compile with TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DUSE_EPDM_COMMON_DEFINES in make\config.mk file

    Note: By default driver uses common defines that is available in the driver package.

12. Big Endian Support
----------------------
   Application has to follow below step to enable the support for Big Endian host (applicable
   to selected PHYs, please refer to user guide)

       Compile with TMP_PHYMOD_EPIL_CPPFLAGS += -DBE_HOST in make/config.mk file

13. Enabling Debug Log
----------------------
    Debug log can be enabled for PHY driver by changing PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_LEVEL
    and PHYMOD_DEBUG_SUB_LEVEL (Sub-Layer debugging) to desired severity level inside phymod_custom_config.h header file.
    PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_LEVEL defines the debug log level for the entire system
    Supported debug log levels are:
       0 - PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_NO_INFO     : No information message is displayed while initialization
                                             except error and diagnostics API log. This is enabled when user does not want initialization
                                             information be displayed.
       1 - PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_CRITICAL_INFO : Display critical information that provides top level view of the
                                             phy chip initialization. This is enabled by default.
       2 - PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_DEBUG_INFO    : This will enable complete debugging info log. Recommended for debug purposes.
       Log priority 0, 1, and 2 denote priority from highest to lowest. For example, when PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_LEVEL is set to
       PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_DEBUG_INFO, log for higher priority (PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_CRITICAL_INFO) will be enabled, as well,
       which will include critical information as well as complete debug information.
    Default severity level is set to critical in phymod_custom_config.h:
    #define PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_LEVEL                  PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_CRITICAL_INFO

    Sub-layer debugging can be enabled or disabled selectively:
    Note: it is enabled for selected layers if PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_LEVEL is set to PHYMOD_LOG_SEVERITY_DEBUG_INFO.
    Following sub-layers are defined as bit fields:
        DEBUG_BCM      0x1    : BCM layer log
        DEBUG_PHYMOD   0x2    : PHYMOD layer log
        DEBUG_DRIVER   0x4    : Chip specific driver log
        DEBUG_MISC     0x8    : Low level debug log from Firmware, SerDes, etc.
        DEBUG_BUS      0x10   : Debug log for MDIO BUS read/write
        DEBUG_DEV      0x20   : Development debug info
    e.g. #define DEBUG_ALL       (DEBUG_BCM | DEBUG_PHYMOD | DEBUG_DRIVER | DEBUG_MISC)
    #define PHYMOD_DEBUG_SUB_LEVEL   DEBUG_ALL

14. Enabling both BaseT and HSIP Macsec PHY simultaneously
    ------------------------------------------------------
    - If the user application requires to enable both BaseT and HSIP Macsec PHY simultaneously, then BASET_HSIP_MACSEC_SUPPORT
        should be defined in the user application's Makefile.

15. General Recommendations
    -----------------------
    - All unused input parameters are recommended to be initialized to zero.

16. Updating utilities path
    -----------------------
    - The driver package sets the default utilities path.  If needed, user can override default path 
      by updating below define in make/config.mk file.
      
      EPIL_UTIL_PATH 

17. Obtaining and using D2XX driver for FTDI devices
    ------------------------------------------------
    - The driver package for FTDI devices can be downloaded from https://ftdichip.com/drivers/d2xx-drivers/.
      Users need to select the correct files for their host OS and HW architecture. To compile and use 
      Broadcom provided reference applications WinTypes.h, ftd2xx.h and libftd2xx.a are needed.  The 
      reference application Makefile needs to be modified to provide path to D2XX driver using FTDI_HOME
      variable.

18. Defining true and false in MACsec DDK source code for applicable PHYs.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------
    - User can define the following flag in their Makefile if the environment does not have true and false definitions.

      BASICDEFS_BOOL_V1


